## Acceptance Criteria

### Must-have

- canonical project rules exist as a first-class project resource
- rules are versioned
- compile produces deterministic outputs for the five core tools
- only SessionFS-managed files may be overwritten by default
- sessions persist `rules_version`, `rules_hash`, `rules_source`, and `instruction_artifacts`
- managed rules files embed a SessionFS marker and version/hash metadata
- active knowledge claims can be injected into compiled rules
- project context can be injected into compiled rules
- rules update path uses optimistic concurrency, not silent overwrite
- enabled tools are explicit, not “all tools by default”
- `sfs rules init/edit/show/compile/push/pull` work
- dashboard Rules tab works
- tests cover:
  - compile determinism
  - overwrite safety
  - version bump only on content change
  - session provenance capture
  - conflict handling

### Should-have

- one-source import flow
- `rules diff` against a session
- MCP `get_rules`
- MCP `get_compiled_rules`
- basic version list in dashboard

### Must not

- do not silently overwrite unmanaged files
- do not manage global rules files in v0.9.9
- do not require LLMs for rules compilation
- do not auto-merge multiple unmanaged tool rule files
- do not let agents directly edit canonical rules
- do not regress existing session capture or resume behavior

